\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$MIC_B^{alone}$\end{document} are the inhibitory concentrations of drugs A and B when acting individually. A FICI ≤0.5 is considered synergistic (S), a FICI >0.5–≤4 is indifferent (I) and a FICI >4 is antagonistic (A).

bThe interaction ratio (IR) was calculated with the following formula: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$IR\ = \ \frac{{{I_o}}}{{{I_e}}}$\end{document}, where Io is considered the observed percentage of inhibition and Ie is the expected percentage of inhibition for a certain combination. Ie is calculated as follows: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}${I_e} = \ A + B - ( {\frac{{AB}}{{100}}} )$\end{document}, where A and B are the inhibition observed for compounds A and B alone. An IR >1.5 is considered synergistic (S), an IR between 0.5 and 1.5 is indifferent (I) and an IR <0.5 is antagonistic (A).
